The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, February 28, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 National Organic Chemical Industries Ltd (Nocil) has been declared a sick company following erosion in its financial health. The Mafatlal Group company has been registered by the Board for Industrial and Financial Reconstruction (BIFR) as a sick industrial company under the Sick Industrial Companies (Special Provision) Act, 1985, Nocil informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.																								 ICI India has completed most of its restructuring by divesting non-core businesses and is now eyeing acquisitions in paints and speciality chemicals segments. Due to the divestments, we have around Rs 200-300 crore surplus cash and the company is ready for growth via acquisitions, managing director Rajiv Jain said.																								 The ministry of small-scale industries and the Federation of Associations of Small Industries of India are jointly organising Indsum Fair and Technology Summit-cum-symposium from February 27 to March 4 in Calcutta. The fair will explore potentials of small industries with a focus on the Northeast.																								 Sidbi Venture Capital Ltd, a fund to assist growth in IT companies, has invested Rs 4 crore in Compulink, a Pune-based software product and services company. ADVERTISEMENT
